Chapter 1: Introduction 

1.1 Background and Motivation 

In aerospace engineering, progress often hinges on dual demands: achieving both higher strength‑to‑weight ratios and greater functional integration in ever‑smaller form‑factors. Traditional machining and additive manufacturing methods are increasingly reaching their limits as components shrink to micro‑ and nano‑scales (e.g., sensors in avionics, micro‑thrusters, structural micro‑features in satellites). 

To address this gap, manufacturing methods need to: 

create features with micron or sub‑micron resolution, 

handle a wide range of materials including metals, ceramics, functional coatings, 

preserve material integrity (minimal heat‑affected zones, minimal collateral damage), 

be flexible and scalable for aerospace applications (e.g., repair, direct writing, on‑orbit manufacturing). 

One technique that stands out is Laser‑Induced Forward Transfer (LIFT), which offers contact‑free deposition of donor material to a receiver substrate via laser pulses. Because it doesn’t rely on nozzles, inks, or contact printing, it sidesteps many of the limitations of traditional micro‑printing (such as clogging, fluid viscosity constraints, or thermal damage over extended dwell times). 

In particular, when ultrafast (femtosecond) lasers are used, the laser‑matter interaction happens faster than significant heat diffusion into surrounding regions. This allows for highly localized energy delivery, reduced collateral damage, and potential for finer feature sizes. Early femtosecond LIFT studies already show sub‑micron transfer footprints (e.g., Cr nanodroplets down to ~300 nm) under appropriate conditions. (ResearchGate) 

In aerospace microfabrication, this capability unlocks several disruptive possibilities: 

Fabrication of miniaturised propulsion sensors with embedded metallic tracks or complex 3D features. 

Direct writing of interconnects on satellite electronics, or repair of defective traces on orbit (no need to remove entire components). 

Additive growth of functionally‑graded materials, layered microstructures for thermal shielding or micro‑actuators. 

Because femtosecond pulses minimise residual thermal damage, the technique is compatible with sensitive materials used in aerospace (e.g., thin‑film coatings, advanced composites). 

Yet despite its promise, femtosecond LIFT remains insufficiently understood, especially when one moves beyond proof‑of‑concept. The key challenges include: 

The ultrafast physics of laser absorption, electron‑lattice non‑equilibrium, melting/vaporisation and subsequent recoil pressure in the donor film. 

The fluid dynamics of droplet/jet ejection: surface tension, viscosity, ambient gas drag, jet breakup, droplet trajectory and landing behaviour. 

The coupling between the above phenomena. For aerospace‑grade deposition, one needs reliable prediction of droplet size, velocity, landing morphology, bonding strength—and simulation is the only practical way to explore the vast parameter space (laser fluence, film thickness, gap distance, material properties) without exhaustive experiments. 

Hence this thesis is motivated by the goal of delivering a predictive computational framework that brings together ultrafast laser interaction and multiphase CFD for LIFT, with an eye toward aerospace micro‑additive manufacturing. 

1.2 Laser‑Induced Forward Transfer (LIFT): Principle and Potential 

LIFT works as follows: A donor substrate (typically transparent to the laser wavelength) is coated with a thin film of the material to be transferred (metal, polymer, composite). A pulsed laser is focused through the transparent substrate onto the donor film. The absorbed energy causes rapid heating, phase change (melting, vaporisation) and mechanical ejection of material toward a nearby receiver substrate. The material then lands, spreads or solidifies, forming the desired deposit. (PMC) 

Important attributes: 

No nozzle/contact printing: avoids issues of viscosity, nozzle clogging, shear stresses in ink. 

Versatility of materials: metals, polymers, ceramics, functional inks, even living cells (in bioprinting variants) have been successfully transferred. (Frontiers) 

High spatial resolution: in some cases, feature sizes ≤10 µm or even sub‑µm have been achieved in LIFT with ultrafast lasers. (sciencedirect.com) 

Rapid processing: as the mechanism is laser‑driven, deposition events can occur on very short timescales, enabling high throughput if suitably engineered. 

From a potential standpoint in aerospace micro‑manufacturing: 

One could directly print metallic interconnects or sensors onto curved surfaces, composite skins, or delicate substrates. 

On‑orbit repair becomes more feasible: imagine a robotic arm with a femtosecond‑laser LIFT head, depositing micro‑patches or new traces in situ. 

Hybrid manufacturing: combining LIFT‑deposited features with conventional additive/subtractive processes for lightweight, high­precision assemblies. 

The absence of significant heat‑affected zones makes this approach compatible with heat‑sensitive substrates (e.g., polymer composites, thin‑film electronic sensors). 

Thus LIFT provides a compelling bridge between microfabrication precision and the functional demands of aerospace systems. 

1.3 Role of Femtosecond Lasers in LIFT 

The move from nanosecond to femtosecond pulses in LIFT brings several key advantages — and complexities. 

Why femtosecond pulses matter: 

The laser‐matter interaction time is shorter than the electron–phonon coupling time in metals (~picoseconds), so electrons absorb laser energy, reach high temperatures, but the lattice remains relatively cold initially. This non‑equilibrium state enables more localized heating, reduces lateral heat conduction, and minimizes damage to surrounding areas. 

Because of the short pulse, the thermal diffusion length is small, leading to very high heating rate, high peak temperature, and potentially more efficient phase change or ablation with less collateral melting. 

Some studies show that femtosecond LIFT can deposit solid‑phase films, transfer transparent materials (via multiphoton absorption), or produce droplets down to ~300 nm diameter. (ResearchGate) 

However, the femtosecond regime also introduces modeling challenges: 

One must consider the Two‑Temperature Model (TTM): electrons and lattice have distinct temperatures and exchange energy via electron–phonon coupling. The TTM is essential for capturing the ultrafast dynamics of absorption and heat transfer. (Wikipedia) 

The phase change (melting/vaporisation) may occur under non‑equilibrium conditions, and the subsequent fluid/jet behaviour begins from an unusual initial state (hot electrons, superheated lattice, high pressure). 

The resulting recoil pressure and jet ejection dynamics may differ significantly from longer‑pulse LIFT due to higher peak pressures, smaller thermal diffusion, and possibly plasma formation. 

For example, the review by Lee et al. (“Laser‑Induced Transfer of Functional Materials”) summarises how ultrafast pulses allow “cleaner” transfers and finer resolution compared with longer pulses. (PMC) 

In an aerospace‑oriented context, this matters because: 

Fine control over deposition size/shape is critical (e.g., micro‑wiring, micro‑sensor patches). 

Minimising thermal damage is essential when working on high‑value composite skins or electronics that cannot tolerate high temperatures. 

The high ejection speeds and tight feature control offered by femtosecond LIFT can enable deposition in constrained geometries or complex 3D architectures. 

Thus your focus on femtosecond‑laser LIFT is very well justified for aerospace microfabrication. 

1.4 Significance in Aerospace Microfabrication 

Linking the LIFT technique to aerospace applications highlights several strategic points: 

Miniaturised sensors and electronics: Aerospace systems increasingly rely on micro‑sensors (e.g., MEMS accelerometers, pressure sensors, thermal sensors). These often need metallic traces, contact pads, or functional thin‑films deposited on unconventional substrates. A nozzle‐free, laser‐based deposition such as LIFT is ideal for direct writing onto curved or composite surfaces. 

Repair and maintenance in constrained environments: In satellites, UAVs or high‑altitude systems, component repair or upgrade is extremely challenging. A robotic femtosecond‑LIFT system could apply patches, reprint traces, or add micro‐features in situ, avoiding full component replacement. 

Advanced materials integration: Aerospace structures increasingly use hybrid materials (composite/metallic alloys, small functional coatings). The ability to deposit thin‑film metals or functional materials directly, with minimal substrate damage, opens up new design freedoms (e.g., embedded micro‑heaters, local thermal shields, sensor networks printed onto structure). 

Lightweight, high‑performance assemblies: By using LIFT to deposit high‑precision features rather than rely on separate manufactured parts, one can reduce mass and assembly complexity. Femtosecond LIFT enables features at smaller scales and potentially in 3D stacks, aligning with aerospace demands for compact, high-performance integration. 

Process fidelity and repeatability: For aerospace qualification, repeatable, predictable deposition behaviour is crucial (especially for sensor or structural integration). A predictive simulation framework (as you propose) helps generate that repeatability, enabling parameter windows to be defined and controlled. 

In short, the significance lies in the convergence of precision microfabrication, materials flexibility, minimal thermal/structural damage, and integration into advanced aerospace systems. 

